===========================================================================
 Chapter 2:                 MUSLIB API FUNCTIONS
===========================================================================

The entries in this chapter are laid out in the following format:


Function foo

Declaration:	int foo(char *bar);

Actions:	This section gives a brief synopsis of the function.

Parameters:	This section describes the meaning and usage of function's
		parameters.

Return value:	This section tells you the number returned from this
		function is absolutely meaningless.  ;->

Remarks:	What you should be aware of.


2.1 - MUSLib Kernel Initialization
==================================

2.1.1 - Function MLinit
-----------------------

Declaration:	void MLinit(void);

Actions:	Initializes the MUS Player Library.

Parameters:	None.

Return value:	None.

Remarks:	This function must be called before using any other API
		functions. Not doing so may result in an undefined behavior.


2.1.2 - Function MLdeinit
-------------------------

Declaration:	void MLdeinit(void);

Actions:	Shuts down the library subsystem and frees used resources.

Parameters:	None.

Return value:	None.

Remarks:	This function is called automatically on program exit and
		it is unnecessary to call it explicitly.


2.1.3 - Function MLinitTimer
----------------------------

Declaration:	int MLinitTimer(int mode);

Actions:	Initializes and starts the timer used for background playing.

Parameters:	`mode' specifies which timer to use. The following constants
		are defined:

			#define TIMER_CNT18_2	0
			#define TIMER_CNT140	1
			#define TIMER_RTC1024	2
			#define TIMER_RTC512	3
			#define TIMER_RTC256	4
			#define TIMER_RTC128	5
			#define TIMER_RTC64	6

		* `TIMER_CNT18_2' uses the standard system timer (IRQ 8)
		  running at 18.2 Hz without reprogramming the interrupt
		  rate. This mode is present only for compatibility reasons
		  and should not be used unless all other modes fail.
		  The internal 140 Hz clock is simulated by issuing more
		  cycles within one 18.2 Hz interrupt. Because of this
		  feature, the music timing is not smooth and some songs
		  sound `jerky'.

		* `TIMER_CNT140' uses the system timer with the interrupt
		  rate reprogrammed to 140 Hz. The system time is kept
		  running at the default rate of 18.2 Hz. This is the
		  recommended mode for most applications.

		* `TIMER_RTC1024' uses the Real Clock Timer (RTC) running at
		  1024 Hz. This timer is only seldom used and as such is an
		  ideal provider of precise timing. However this timer is
		  available only under plain DOS. Most other systems like
		  Windows, OS/2 or Linux DOS Emulator don't allow the
		  applications to use this timer. Care should be taken if
		  you are writing protected-mode application. The driver
		  for this timer works fine under PMODE/W, but fails if run
		  under DOS/4GW.

		* The timers `TIMER_RTC512' till `TIMER_RTC64' are almost
		  the same as `TIMER_RTC1024', except for they re-program
		  the RTC interrupt rate. The reason for adding these timers
		  was to decrease system load by reducing the number of
		  interrupt requests. Anyway, 1024Hz is too precise for any
		  music since the default MUS timer ticks at 140Hz only.

Return value:   Returns zero in the timer was succesfully initialized, and
		non-zero if an error occurred or an invalid `mode' number
		was specified.


2.1.4 - Function MLshutdownTimer
--------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLshutdownTimer(void);

Actions:        Shuts down any running timer.

Parameters:	None.

Return value:	Returns 0 upon successful timer termination, and non-zero
		if an error occurred or the timer was not initialized.


2.2 - Sound Driver-Related Functions
====================================

2.2.1 - Function MLaddDriver
----------------------------

Declaration:	int MLaddDriver(struct driverBlock *newDriver);

Actions:	Adds the driver block to the active driver list.

Parameters:	`newDriver' is a pointer to a driver descriptor block.
		The following driver descriptors are defined:

			DUMMYdriver
			OPL2driver
			OPL3driver
			AWE32driver
			MPU401driver
			SBMIDIdriver

Return value:	Returns 0 if the driver was successfully added, and non-zero
		if the driver was already in the list or if the driver could
		not be initialized.

Remarks:        Failing to call this function results in no music being
		played back. By default only the DUMMYdriver is present in
		the list and all other drivers must be added manually.


2.2.2 - Function MLfindDriver
-----------------------------

Declaration:	struct driverBlock *MLfindDriver(uint driverID);

Actions:	Finds the driver descriptor block associated with the driver
		identification code.

Parameters:	`driverID' may be one of the following constants:

			#define DRV_DUMMY 	0x0000
			#define DRV_OPL2        0x0001
			#define DRV_OPL3	0x0002
			#define DRV_AWE32 	0x0003
			#define DRV_MPU401	0x0004
			#define DRV_SBMIDI	0x0005

Return value:	If the driver block does not exist or the driverID contains
		an invalid number, the function returns NULL. Otherwise
		the function returns the pointer to the driver descriptor
		block.

		In the current version of MUSLib the driverBlock looks like
		this:

		struct driverBlock {
			struct driverBlock *next;
			uint	driverID;
			char	*name;
			uint	datasize;

			int	(*initDriver)(void);
			int	(*deinitDriver)(void);
			int	(*driverParam)(uint message, uint param1,
					void *param2);
			int	(*loadBank)(int fd, uint bankNumber);
			int	(*detectHardware)(uint port, uchar irq,
					uchar dma);
			int	(*initHardware)(uint port, uchar irq,
					uchar dma);
			int	(*deinitHardware)(void);

			void	(*playNote)(struct musicBlock *mus,
					uint channel, uchar note, int volume);
			void	(*releaseNote)(struct musicBlock *mus,
					uint channel, uchar note);
			void	(*pitchWheel)(struct musicBlock *mus,
					uint channel, int pitch);
			void	(*changeControl)(struct musicBlock *mus,
					uint channel, uchar controller,
					int value);
			void	(*playMusic)(struct musicBlock *mus);
			void	(*stopMusic)(struct musicBlock *mus);
			void	(*changeVolume)(struct musicBlock *mus,
					uint volume);
			void	(*pauseMusic)(struct musicBlock *mus);
			void	(*unpauseMusic)(struct musicBlock *mus);
			int	(*sendMIDI)(uint command, uint par1,
					uint par2);
			uint	state; /* 0-not initialized, <>0-initialized */
		};

Remarks:	The driver descriptor block is an internal data structure
		which will be changed to implement new features. Therefore
		the application programs should not rely on its contents.


2.2.3 - Function MLinitDriver
-----------------------------

Declaration:	int MLinitDriver(uint driverID);

Actions:	Initializes internal driver data.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.

Return value:	Returns 0 if the driver was successfully initialized, and
		non-zero otherwise.

Remarks:	This function is automatically called by MLaddDriver, so
		it is unnecessary to use this functions unless you have
		a good reason for it.


2.2.4 - Function MLdeinitDriver
-------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLdeinitDriver(uint driverID);

Actions:	Deinitializes (shuts down) the driver.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.

Return value:	Returns 0 if the driver was successfully shut down, and
		non-zero otherwise.

Remarks:	This function is automatically called by MLdeinit.


2.2.5 - Function MLdriverParam
------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLdriverParam(uint driverID, uint message, uint param1,
				  void *param2);

Actions:	Sets driver-specific parameter.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.
		`message' may be one of these constants:

			#define DP_NOTHING	0x0000
			#define DP_SYSEX	0x0001
			#define DP_SINGLE_VOICE	0x0002

		* `DP_NOTHING' is a no-operation placeholder.
		* `DP_SYSEX' sends a System Exclusive message to a MIDI port.
		  `param1' is the length in bytes and `param2' points to
		  an array of bytes containing the SysEx data (including the
		  0xF0 or 0xF7 event header).
		* `DP_SINGLE_VOICE' is understood by OPL2/OPL3 drivers.
		  If `param1' is zero, the driver uses double-voice
		  instruments if available; if non-zero, the driver is
		  forced to use always one voice. `param2' is ignored.

		Other message codes may be defined, but codes in the range
		0x0000-0x00FF are reserved to the MUSLib system.

Return value:	Returns 0 if no error occurred, and non-zero otherwise.

Remarks:	In general, the return value of this function may be
		driver-specific.


2.2.6 - Function MLloadBank
---------------------------

Declaration:	int MLloadBank(uint driverID, int fd, uint bankNumber);

Actions:	Loads an instrument (patch) bank.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.
		`fd' is a file descriptor (handle) of a file containing
		the instrument bank. The file must be opened in binary mode.
		`bankNumber' is the bank number into which the instruments
		are to be loaded. Some drivers (OPL2/OPL3) ignore this
		parameter.

Return value:   Returns 0 if the bank was successfully loaded, and non-zero
		otherwise (invalid file, file read error, not enough memory,
		hardware error, etc).

Remarks:	The patch bank should be loaded before the hardware is
		initialized, because some sound devices are initialized
		by loading a set of instruments and must be reinitialized
		in order to change the set of instruments.


2.2.7 - Function MLdetectHardware
---------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLdetectHardware(uint driverID, short port, short irq,
				     short dma);

Actions:	Detects the presence of the hardware.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.
		`port', 'irq' and 'dma' are optional device-specific
		parameters. Some devices don't use DMA or don't generate
		any interrupts. In this case the respective parameter
		is unused and should be -1.

Return value:	Returns zero if the hardware was NOT detected, and non-zero
		otherwise.

Remarks:	Incorrect values of `port', 'irq' and 'dma' may hang the
		system.


2.2.8 - Function MLinitHardware
-------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLinitHardware(uint driverID, short port, short irq,
				   short dma);

Actions:	Initializes the hardware for use by MUSLib.

Parameters:	see MLdetectHardware for description

Return value:	Returns 0 if the hardware was initialized successfully, and
		non-zero otherwise.


2.2.9 - Function MLdeinitHardware
---------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLdeinitHardware(uint driverID);

Actions:	Shuts down all sounds and resets the hardware to the
		default setting.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.

Return value:	Returns 0 if the hardware was reset successfully, and
		non-zero otherwise.


2.3 - Music Control Functions
=============================

2.3.1 - Function MLallocHandle
------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLallocHandle(uint driverID);

Actions:	Allocates a free handle and initializes internal data
		structures.

Parameters:	`driverID' is the driver identifier. The driver must be
		in the active driver list.

Return value:	Returns a valid music handle or a negative number if an
		error occurred (no more handles are available, invalid
		driver identifier or not enough memory).

Remarks:	The current implementation allows up to 4 handles to be
		allocated at the same time.


2.3.2 - Function MLfreeHandle
-----------------------------

Declaration:	int MLfreeHandle(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Stops music if still playing, frees any allocated resources
		and finally marks the handle as unused.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns 0 if the handle was successfully freed, and non-zero
		otherwise (invalid handle).

Remarks:	This function incorporates the actions of MLstop and
		MLfreeMUS.


2.3.3 - Function MLloadMUS
--------------------------

Declaration:	int MLloadMUS(uint musHandle, int fd, uint memoryFlags);

Actions:	Loads a MUS file into memory.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.
		`fd' is a file descriptor (handle) of a MUS file. The file
		must be opened in binary mode.
		`memoryFlags' contains the following bits:

		  ÖÄ7ÄÂÄ6ÄÂÄ5ÄÂÄ4ÄÂÄ3ÄÂÄ2ÄÂÄ1ÄÂÄ0Ä·
		  ş       Unused      łXMSłEMSłLowş
		  ÓÄÄÄÁÄÄÄÁÄÄÄÁÄÄÄÁÄÄÄÁÄÄÄÁÄÄÄÁÄÄÄ˝

		  bit 0: if set, allows the file to be loaded into low
			 (conventional) memory; if reset, keeps the file
			 from loading low.
		  bit 1: enables loading into EMS memory
		  bit 2: enables loading into XMS (HIMEM) memory
		  bits 3-15 (3-31): unused, should be zero

		If the file is too small it will be loaded low regardless
		whether the EMS/XMS memory was specified or not. This
		measure prevents the program from wasting memory, because
		the MUSLib memory manager keeps a fixed-size buffer (in the
		order of 1KB) for faster access to the EMS/XMS memory. If
		the requested file is smaller than the buffer, the buffer
		is not allocated and the file is forced to load low.

		By default you can leave all these bits set and let the
		program decide which memory to use.

Return value:   Returns zero if the file was loaded successfully and
		non-zero if an error occurred (invalid music handle, file
		read error, invalid file contents or not enough memory).

Remarks:        The music handle should be empty, that means if you want
		to reuse a handle, you must call MLfreeMUS first.

		Under 32-bit protected mode version, bits 1 and 2 are ignored
		and the EMS/XMS support is disabled.


2.3.4 - Function MLfreeMUS
--------------------------

Declaration:	int MLfreeMUS(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Frees any loaded music file data from memory and stops the
		music if still playing.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns zero if the music was successfully freed and
		non-zero otherwise.


2.3.5 - Function MLplay
-----------------------

Declaration:	int MLplay(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Starts music play back. If the music was playing or paused,
		the song is rewound to the beginning and restarted.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns zero on success, and non-zero if an invalid music
		handle was specified.


2.3.6 - Function MLstop
-----------------------

Declaration:	int MLstop(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Stops any playing or paused music.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns zero on success, and non-zero if an invalid music
		handle was specified.


2.3.7 - Function MLpause
------------------------

Declaration:	int MLpause(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Pauses music. May be nested more than once.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns zero on success, and non-zero if an invalid music
		handle was specified.

Remarks:	The music may be paused more than once at one time.
		To restore the original state, every call to MLpause
		must have a corresponding call to MLunpause.


2.3.8 - Function MLunpause
--------------------------

Declaration:	int MLunpause(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Unpauses (restores) music. May be nested more than once.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns zero on success, and non-zero if an invalid music
		handle was specified.

Remarks:	The music may be paused more than once at one time.
		To restore the original state, every call to MLpause
		must have an corresponding call to MLunpause.


2.3.9 - Function MLgetState
---------------------------

Declaration:	int MLgetState(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Returns actual music playing state.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns a negative number if an invalid music handle was
		specified or one the following constants:

			#define ST_EMPTY	0
			#define ST_STOPPED	1
			#define ST_PLAYING	2
			#define ST_PAUSED	3

		* `ST_EMPTY' means the block is empty and cannot be played
		* `ST_STOPPED' means the block contains valid music, but
		  is not playing or was stopped
		* `ST_PLAYING' means the music is playing right now
		* value >= `ST_PAUSED' means the music is paused

Remarks:	Because the music plays on background, its state may change
		unexpectedly and the value returned from this function may
		not reflect the reality at the time it is evaluated.


2.3.10 - Function MLsetVolume
-----------------------------

Declaration:	int MLsetVolume(uint musHandle, uint volume);

Actions:	Changes music volume.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.
		`volume' is a new music volume. The default value 256 means
		normal volume. Values below 256 cause the music to be
		attenuated and values above 256 amplify the music if
		possible. However volume value should not exceed 512,
		because too high values might cause arithmetical overflow
		and undefined results.

Return value:	Returns zero on success, and non-zero if an invalid music
		handle was specified.


2.3.11 - Function MLgetVolume
-----------------------------

Declaration:	int MLgetVolume(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Reads actual music volume.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns the music volume value or a negative number if an
		invalid music handle was specified.


2.3.12 - Function MLsetLoopCount
--------------------------------

Declaration:	int MLsetLoopCount(uint musHandle, int count);

Actions:	Sets the number how many times the music should be played.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.
		`count' is the number of loops. If set to -1, the music
		loops infinitely. 0 and 1 means no looping, play exactly
		once; 2 means play twice, etc.

Return value:	Returns zero on success, and non-zero if an invalid music
		handle was specified.


2.3.13 - Function MLgetBlock
----------------------------

Declaration:	struct musicBlock *MLgetBlock(uint musHandle);

Actions:	Returns an address of an internal music descriptor block
		structure.

Parameters:	`musHandle' should be a valid music handle.

Return value:	Returns NULL if the specified block is not allocated or
		an invalid music handle was specified. Otherwise returns
		the address of the descriptor block.

		The music descriptor block is declared in this version of
		MUSLib in this way:

		struct musicBlock {
			uint	state;	/* music block state, see ST_xxx */
			uint	number;	/* block id number */
			uint	volume;
			uint	loopcount;
			uint	channelMask;
			uint	percussMask;
			ulong	time;
			ulong	ticks;
			uint	playingcount;
			uint	channelcount;
			struct memoryBlock	score;
			struct driverBlock	*driver;
			void			*driverdata;
		};

Remarks:	The music descriptor block is an internal data structure
		which will be changed to implement new features. Therefore
		the application programs should not rely on its contents.


2.4 - Mixer Functions
=====================

2.4.1 - Function SBsetMixer
---------------------------

Declaration:	void SBsetMixer(uint SBport, uchar index, uchar data);

Actions:	Writes one Sound Blaster Pro/16 mixer register.

Parameters:	`SBport' is the Sound Blaster base port (default 0x220).
		`index' is the mixer register number.
		`data' is the byte to be written to the mixer.

Return value:	None.

Remarks:	See [sblast09] for more information about the Sound Blaster
		mixer.


2.4.2 - Function SBgetMixer
---------------------------

Declaration:	int SBgetMixer(uint SBport, uchar index);

Actions:	Reads one Sound Blaster Pro/16 mixer register.

Parameters:	`SBport' is the Sound Blaster base port (default 0x220).
		`index' is the mixer register number.

Return value:   Returns the byte read from the mixer.


2.4.3 - Function SBdetectMixer
------------------------------

Declaration:	int SBdetectMixer(uint port);

Actions:	Detects the presence of Sound Blaster mixer.

Parameters:	`port' is the Sound Blaster base port (default 0x220).

Return value:	Returns zero if the mixer is not found and non-zero
		otherwise.

Remarks:	This function may be useful for distinguishing between
		Sound Blaster (does not have a mixer) and Sound Blaster-
		Pro/Pro II/16 (has a mixer). Another way could be reading
		the DSP version (see [sblast09]).


2.5 - Miscellaneous Functions
=============================

2.5.1 - Function MLparseBlaster
-------------------------------

Declaration:	uint MLparseBlaster(const char *format, ...);

Actions:	Parses the BLASTER environment variable and returns the
		obtained values.

Parameters:	`format' is a string of one-letter field names delimited
		by colons (':'). The string may also contain the following
		special characters:

		* '#' - parse as decimal number
		* '$' - parse as hexadecimal number

		These modifiers affect the rest of the format string and
		are not local to the field name they precede. Hexadecimal
		mode is selected by default.

		`...' is a list of pointers to unsigned integers (uint *),
		that will hold the obtained values.

Return value:	Returns 0 if the BLASTER variable does not exist or none
		of the specified fields were present. Otherwise, the
		returned value is a bit-map with each bit equivalent to
		one field specified in the format string. The bit is set
		if the field is present, and not set if the field is absent.
		The first field maps to bit 0, the second to bit 1, etc.

Remarks:	Do not make errors by sending the destination variable value
		instead of its address. This kind of error will not be
		signalled by the compiler and may be difficult to find.

		Do not forget to delimit the fields by colons, otherwise
		all values would be stored into the first destination
		variable.

Example:	Suppose this setting:
		  BLASTER=A220 D1 I5 P330 T6

		MLparseBlaster("A:#D:I:$E", &port, &dma, &irq, &EMUport);

		The function returns 7 to indicate that 'A' (1), 'D' (2)
		and 'I' (4) fields were found, but the 'E' (8) field wasn't.
		The respective variables will be set the values read from
		the BLASTER string except EMUport, which will be left
		untouched. Also note 'A' and 'E' fields are parsed as
		hexadecimal numbers unlike 'D' and 'I' which are in decimal.


===========================================================================
 Chapter 3:                 ADDITIONAL INFORMATION
===========================================================================

3.1 - Hardware and Software Requirements
----------------------------------------

* processor 386 or higher
* supported sound cards:
    - Adlib, Sound Blaster (OPL2)
    - Sound Blaster Pro II, SB 16 (OPL3)
    - Sound Blaster AWE32 (EMU 8000)
    - Roland MPU-401 MIDI port (UART mode)
    - Sound Blaster's built-in MIDI port
* PC-AT compatible machine (with standard Real-Time Clock chipset and
  CMOS memory layout)
* MS-DOS version 3.0+
* about 128 KB of free conventional memory
* up to 64 KB of EMS or XMS for each music file (optional, not required)


3.2 - Future Plans
------------------

* digital playback on Sound Blaster (use samples instead of FM synthesis)
* full screen display (not console-like) with graphical bars and blobs
* MIDI file support
* OPL4 support -- if anyone knows something about it, let the world know
* Gravis Ultrasound, WaveBlaster, Aria, ESS688, ... support


3.3 - Known Bugs
----------------

File D_INTROA.MUS from original DOOM.WAD is not played correctly (some voices
sound too loud). I can't figure out why.

The RTC-timer 32-bit protected mode driver doesn't work properly under DOS/4GW,
while everything seems OK under PMODE/W. Strange. Needs some research.


